 organized, how the readers and readings were selected, and how the process affected the relationship between workers and factory owners. Because of the reader, cigar factory workers were far more cultured and in touch with the political currents of the day than other workers. But it was not only the reading material, which provided political and literary information that yielded self-education, that influenced the workers; the act of being read to increased the discipline and timing of the artisan's job.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aOral reading. 0aTobacco industryzCubaxHistory. 0aTobacco industryzPuerto RicoxHistory. 0aTobacco industryzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aTobacco workerszCubaxHistory. 0aTobacco workerszPuerto RicoxHistory. 0aTobacco workerszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh1 aGrasberg, Judith E.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292793361423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292793361/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK